\r (2 Kgs 18:13-27; 2 Chr. 32:1-19)
\p
\v 1 In the fourteenth year¦293971 of \add the reign of\add* King Hezkiyah \add (Hezekiah¦293973)\add*, Assyria's¦293978 King Sennacherib¦293975 \add ≈attacked\add* Yehudah's¦293983 fortified¦293984 cities¦293982 and captured them.
\v 2 Then¦293987 from Lakish \add (Lachish¦293997)\add*, the Assyrian king sent \add ≈his top negotiator\add* to King¦293988 Hezekiah¦294002 in Yerushalem¦293998 \add (Jerusalem)\add* with a large army. He \add ≈stopped\add* by the aqueduct at the upper¦294008 pool on the road to the field¦294010 \add ≈where women wash clothes\add*,
\v 3 and Hilkiyah's son Elyakim, \add ≈the palace supervisor\add*, went¦294013 out to meet him, \add ≈taking\add* Shevna the \add ≈administrator\add*, and Asaf's¦294028 son Yoah¦294025 the \add ≈secretary¦294024\add*.
\v 4 The \add ≈negotiator\add* instructed them, “Tell Hezkiyah that¦294052 Assyria's¦294048 powerful king wants to know \add ≈who or what you think you're trusting in to rescue you\add*?
\v 5 Your plan and war¦294063 preparations are \add ≈only hot air\add*, so who are you relying on \add that encourages you\add* to rebel¦294070 against¦294071 me?
\v 6 Listen, if it's Egypt \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add*, \add that's like\add* trusting a staff¦294077 made from a splintered reed. If a man were to lean on it, it would pierce¦294090 his palm¦294089—that's what relying on Egypt's¦294083 King¦294093 Far-oh is like for those¦294098 who put their trust in him.
\v 7 \add ≈But¦294101\add* if you tell me that you're relying¦294109 on your god¦294108 Yahweh¦294107, hasn't Hezkiyah¦294115 removed¦294114 his hilltop¦294118 shrines¦294118 and altars, and \add forced all\add* Yehudah¦294123 to worship¦294128 him in front¦294125 of the altar¦294126 there in Yerushalem¦294124?
\p
\v 8 “\add ≈So¦294130\add* now, make¦294131 a deal with my master¦294135, the Assyrian king¦294136. Let me give¦294138 you two¦294140 thousand¦294140 horses¦294141 if you can \add find that many\add* riders¦294147 for them.
\v 9 How could you \add even\add* repel a captain who's one of the least of my master's¦294157 servants¦294156 \add ≈since\add* you've¦294159 been relying¦294159 on Egypt¦294163 for chariots¦294164 and¦294150 horsemen¦294165 \add ≈to rescue you\add*?
\v 10 \add ≈Also¦294167, listen,\add* I didn't come here to destroy this \add ≈region\add* without¦294168 Yahweh—\add it was\add* Yahweh who told me to come \add *here\add* and¦294167 destroy \add @this nation\add*.”
\p
\v 11 Then¦294186 Elyakim and Shevna and Yoah¦294189 \add ≈asked\add* the \add ≈negotiator\add*, “Please speak Aramaic¦294201 to your servants¦294200, because¦294202 we understand¦294203 it. Don't¦294205 speak to us \add ≈in Hebrew\add* in the \add ≈hearing\add* of the people¦294211 who are \add up\add* on the wall¦294215.”
